'''''La femme qui ne supportait pas les ordinateurs''''' (''The woman who could not stand computers'') is a 1986 [[interactive fiction]] [[video game]] developed by French company Froggy Software. The game was designed by Chine Lanzmann and programmed by Jean-Louis Le Breton for [[Apple II]] computers. The player character is a woman who faces several seducers, one of them being a computer named Ordine, who ruthlessly usurps the right to be the only woman's love.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jankowski|first=Filip|date=2019-04-15|title=The Presence of Female Designers in French Video Game Industry, 1985–1993|url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/1555412019841954|journal=Games and Culture|volume=15|issue=6|language=en|doi=10.1177/1555412019841954|issn=1555-4120|page=6|s2cid=150836593}}</ref>

The game takes place on the Calvados network, the network used by the two authors of the game at the time. It imitates its interface and services (for example, messages between users, global chat room, AFP dispatches), as if the player's computer were connected to it. One also meets, in a general chat room, the pseudonyms of the network's users at the time (for example, "Lumbroglio" for Lionel Lumbroso, "Chine" for Chine Lanzmann, "Pepe Louis" for the founder of Froggy Software Jean-Louis Le Breton, "Benv" for François Benveniste).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Labrande|first=Hugo|title=IF Theory Reader|publisher=Transcript On Press|year=2011|editor-last=Jackson-Mead|editor-first=Kevin|location=Boston, MA|pages=406|chapter=Racontons une histoire ensemble: History and Characteristics of the French IF|editor-last2=Wheeler|editor-first2=J. Robinson}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jankowski|first=Filip|date=2021|title=Beyond the French Touch: The Contestataire Moment in French Adventure Digital Games (1984-1990)|url=http://gamestudies.org/2101/articles/jankowski#_ednref3|journal=Game Studies|volume=21|issue=1|issn=1604-7982|access-date=2021-06-12}}</ref>

==Legacy==
The game received a negative review from ''Tilt'' on its release.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Desmedt|first=Patrice|title=La femme qui ne supportait pas les ordinateurs|year=1986|journal=Tilt|volume=31|pages=128–129}}</ref>

''La femme qui ne supportait pas les ordinateurs'' is regarded as one of the first video games about [[cyber harassment]] and female experience online,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jankowski|first=Filip|date=2019-04-15|title=The Presence of Female Designers in French Video Game Industry, 1985–1993|url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/1555412019841954|journal=Games and Culture|volume=15|issue=6|language=en|doi=10.1177/1555412019841954|issn=1555-4120|page=5|s2cid=150836593}}</ref> and one of the first games with an overtly feminist message.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jankowski|first=Filip|date=2017|title=Political and Social Issues in French Digital Games, 1982–1993|url=https://ruj.uj.edu.pl/xmlui/bitstream/handle/item/65330/jankowski_political_and_social_issues_in_french_digital_games_2017.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y|journal=TransMissions|volume=2|pages=167}}</ref>

